<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="37" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1175,1722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,343,1455,1481]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name is a combination of 
<emphasis box="[744,837,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">vulcano</emphasis>
(Latin for volcano), derived from 
<emphasis box="[1273,1380,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Vulcanos</emphasis>
, the Roman god of fire, for the mud volcano habitat in which it was collected, combined with 
<taxonomicName box="[1202,1288,1496,1521]" class="Malacostraca" family="Callianassidae" genus="Calliax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1202,1288,1496,1521]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Calliax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The gender is feminine, as in 
<taxonomicName box="[358,444,1536,1561]" class="Malacostraca" family="Callianassidae" genus="Calliax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[358,444,1536,1561]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Calliax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1175,1722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1575,1601]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Remarks:</emphasis>
The new genus is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Sakai &amp; Turkay, 1999" authorityName="Sakai &amp; Turkay" authorityYear="1999" box="[659,1073,1576,1602]" class="Malacostraca" family="Callianassidae" genus="Bathycalliax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[659,807,1576,1601]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Bathycalliax</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sakai" box="[814,1073,1576,1602]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" refString="Sakai K. &amp; Turkay, M. (1999) A new subfamily, Bathycalliacinae n. subfam., for Bathycalliax geomar n. gen., n. sp. from the deep water cold seeps off Oregon, USA (Crustacea, Decapoda, Callianassidae). Senckenbergiana Biologica 79 (2), 203 - 209." type="journal article" year="1999">
Sakai &amp; Türkay, 
<number box="[1014,1073,1576,1602]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
with respect to the presence of epipods on Mxp 
<number box="[343,355,1616,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
to P 
<number box="[410,426,1616,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="4.0">4</number>
, the shape of Mxp 
<number box="[645,658,1616,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
, the shape of P 
<number box="[835,848,1616,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
propodus, the general shape of the tailfan, and the shape of the eyes, which lack a cornea. 
<taxonomicName box="[633,808,1656,1681]" class="Malacostraca" family="Callianassidae" genus="Vulcanocalliax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n.gen.">
<emphasis box="[633,808,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Vulcanocalliax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[818,890,1656,1682]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">n.gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[1051,1199,1656,1681]" class="Malacostraca" family="Callianassidae" genus="Bathycalliax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1051,1199,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Bathycalliax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the absence of a dorsomedian carina, the absence of cardiac sulci, and the absence of an exopod on Mxp 
<number box="[1183,1196,1696,1722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
